-- English version
INSERT INTO posts (slug, title, date, summary, tags, category, content, published, language)
VALUES (
  '2026-03-26-superposition-memorization-double-descent-en',
  'Superposition, Memorization, and Double Descent',
  '2026-03-26',
  'Anthropic toy model study on how neural networks transition between two superposition regimes when trained on finite datasets: storing individual datapoints (overfitting) vs learning generalizable features (generalization). Double descent emerges at the transition between these regimes. Visualizations in m=2 hidden dimensions reveal clean geometric structure in hidden activations even when weight matrices appear messy.',
  ARRAY['Superposition', 'Memorization', 'Double Descent', 'Mechanistic Interpretability', 'Toy Model', 'Anthropic', 'Research Notes'],
  '연구노트',
  E'# Superposition, Memorization, and Double Descent\n\n**Source:** Anthropic (Transformer Circuits Thread)\n**Authors:** Tom Henighan, Shan Carter, Tristan Hume, Nelson Elhage, Robert Lasenby, Stanislav Fort, Nicholas Schiefer, Christopher Olah\n**Link:** [transformer-circuits.pub](https://transformer-circuits.pub/2023/toy-double-descent/index.html)\n**Date:** January 5, 2023\n\n---\n\n## TL;DR\n\nWhen neural networks are trained on finite datasets, they exhibit two distinct regimes: **storing individual datapoints in superposition (overfitting)** and **learning generalizable features in superposition (generalization)**. **Double descent** emerges as the model transitions between these two regimes.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Background and Motivation\n\nPrior work by Elhage et al. (2022) demonstrated that neural networks use **superposition** to represent more features than available neurons in toy models. That study used infinite data, where models always learn generalizable features.\n\nThis work extends to **finite datasets**. All real neural networks train on finite data, meaning overfitting is always possible. Core question: **How does superposition change with finite data?**\n\n---\n\n## 2. Experimental Setup\n\n### 2.1 Model Architecture\n\n**ReLU Output Model:**\n- Input: n = 10,000 dimensional sparse vectors\n- Hidden layer: m dimensions (primarily m = 2 for visualization)\n- Output reconstruction: x'' = ReLU(W^T · h + b)\n- Encoding: h = W · x (linear encoding)\n\n### 2.2 Data Generation\n\n- Each feature x_i = 0 with probability S = 0.999 (99.9% sparse)\n- Non-zero values sampled from Uniform[0, 1]\n- All input vectors normalized to unit norm → facilitates memorization\n- Finite dataset size T systematically varied\n\n### 2.3 Loss Function\n\n> L = (1/T) Σ_x Σ_i I_i · (x_i - x''_i)²\n\nMSE reconstruction error with uniform importance weights (I_i = 1).\n\n### 2.4 Training Configuration\n\n| Component | Value |\n|-----------|-------|\n| **Optimizer** | Full-batch AdamW |\n| **Total steps** | 50,000 |\n| **Learning rate** | 2,500 step linear warmup → 1e-3 → cosine decay to 0 |\n| **Weight decay** | 1e-2 |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Key Finding: Two Distinct Regimes\n\n### 3.1 Overfitting Regime (Small Datasets)\n\nWith small datasets, the model **stores individual training datapoints in superposition**.\n\n- Each training example is encoded as a **distinct direction** in hidden space\n- Instead of learning features, the model treats each datapoint as a "feature"\n- Visualizing weight matrix W columns shows **messy, unstructured patterns**\n- However, visualizing hidden activations h_i = W · X_i reveals **clean geometric structure** (regular polygons, orthogonal arrangements)\n\nKey insight: **Overfitting corresponds to storing data points, rather than features, in superposition.**\n\n### 3.2 Generalizing Regime (Large Datasets)\n\nWith sufficiently large datasets, the model learns **generalizable features in superposition**, consistent with prior work (Elhage et al., 2022).\n\n- Abstract feature representations shared across many training examples\n- Weight matrix columns form regular polygon structures — identical to infinite data experiments\n- Correct reconstruction on novel inputs → true generalization\n\n### 3.3 Weight Space vs Hidden Activation Space\n\nThe most striking visualization finding:\n\n- **Visualizing W columns**: Overfitting models appear structureless (messy)\n- **Visualizing hidden activations h_i**: Overfitting models show **clean structure** — training datapoints form regular geometric arrangements\n\nThis means models do not overfit "messily" — they **systematically arrange datapoints in superposition** with organized geometric structure.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Double Descent\n\nGradually increasing dataset size reveals a characteristic **double descent** pattern in test loss:\n\n1. **Phase 1 — Initial decrease**: Test loss drops as more data provides useful information\n2. **Phase 2 — Increase (overfitting peak)**: When dataset size approaches the model''s "memorization capacity," the model attempts to store all data individually → test loss increases\n3. **Phase 3 — Second decrease (generalization)**: As data exceeds memorization capacity, individual storage becomes infeasible → model transitions to learning generalizable features → test loss decreases again\n\n**Transition sharpness:** The transition between regimes is relatively **sharp**, with weight decay and learning rate schedules significantly affecting the transition point. Lower weight decay produces sharper double descent.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Significance and Implications\n\n### 5.1 Mechanistic Interpretability\n\n- **New understanding of overfitting**: Overfitting is not a "messy" phenomenon but a structured process that systematically stores datapoints using superposition principles\n- **Implications for interpretability tools**: Examining weights directly cannot reveal overfitting structure; hidden activation analysis is necessary to uncover the true organization\n\n### 5.2 Implications for Real Networks\n\n- Real large-scale models likely employ similar strategies: superposition-based individual storage occurs for data beyond the model''s generalization capacity\n- Superposition may be central to the mechanism of overfitting\n\n### 5.3 New Perspective on Double Descent\n\n- Double descent reinterpreted as a **transition between two different superposition strategies**: datapoint storage → feature storage\n- This provides a mechanistic explanation for why double descent occurs\n\n---\n\n## 6. Connection to Prior Work\n\n- **Elhage et al. (2022), "Toy Models of Superposition"**: Prior work studying superposition with infinite data. This paper extends to finite data.\n- **Nakkiran et al. (2019), "Deep Double Descent"**: Original discovery of the double descent phenomenon. This paper provides a mechanistic interpretation.\n- **Belkin et al. (2019), "Reconciling Modern ML with Bias-Variance Trade-off"**: Analysis of behavior at the interpolation threshold. This paper reinterprets through the superposition lens.',
  true,
  'en'
)
